name: The Shake
author: Neal McCoy
lyrics:
Some men are attracted to a pair of big blue eyes.
It takes a pretty face to make their temperature rise. 
Looks aren't that important, just icing on the cake. 
What really turns me on is the shake. 
Shake it to the left, Shake it to the right. 
Come on baby, you know what I like. 
Shake it real funky, shake it real low. 
Shake it til you can't shake it no more. 
It's a natural attraction, Mother Nature wouldn't make a mistake. 
What really turns me on is the shake. 
Eve first said to Adam, Which outfit do you like? 
The maple or the fig leaf?  Now, Honey, they both look nice. 
Clothes don't mean that much to me.  You better go and ask the snake. 
What really turns me on is the shake.  
Shake it to the left, Shake it to the right. 
Come on baby, you know what I like. 
Shake it real funky, shake it real low. 
Shake it til you can't shake it no more. 
Gary Indiana, Mobile Alabama, Phoenix Arizona, Bismark North Dakota, 
New York, L.A., Houston, Tampa Bay, London, Tokyo, everywhere you go. 
Shake it to the left, Shake it to the right. 
Come on baby, you know what I like. 
Shake it real funky, shake it real low. 
Shake it til you can't shake it no more.

name: Is Not This The Land Of Beulah
author: The Isaacs
lyrics:
I am dwelling on the mountain, where the golden sunlight gleams
 O’er a land whose wondrous beauty far exceeds my fondest dreams;
 Where the air is pure, ethereal, laden with the breath of flow’rs,
 They are blooming by the fountain, ’Neath the amaranthine bow’rs
 Is not this the land of Beulah? Blessed, blessed land of light,
 Where the flowers bloom forever, And the sun is always bright!
I can see far down the mountain, where I wandered weary years,
 Often hindered in my journey by the ghosts of doubts and fears;
 Broken vows and disappointments thickly sprinkled all the way,
 But the Spirit led, unerring, to the land I hold today.
I am drinking from the fountain, Where I ever would abide;
 For I’ve tasted life’s pure river, And my soul is satisfied;
 There’s no thirsting for life’s pleasures, Nor adorning, rich and gay,
 For I’ve found a richer treasure, One that fadeth not away.
Tell me not of heavy crosses, Nor of burdens hard to bear,
 For I’ve found this great salvation makes each burden light appear;
 And I love to follow Jesus, gladly counting all but dross,
 Worldly honors all forsaking for the glory of the cross.

name: River Of Tears
author: Doyle Lawson & Quicksilver
lyrics:
To young and proud parents a baby is born.
They both weep softly as he’s placed in her arms.
While just one floor below them cries a family in grief
For a loved one crossed Jordon their maker to meet.
A handsome young man walks the isle with his bride
The onlookers proudly wipe tears from their eyes.
A few short years later the papers are filed.
As they both cry in anger in a fight for their child.
Winding through life, runs a river of tears
flowing deep with emotions with each passing year.
Tears of pain and joy, tears of gain and loss
Time and again we must cross the river of tears.
Two teen-age solders march bravely to war
To battle for freedom on some distant shore.
One returns safely to tears of great joy
While the other's folks morn for the loss of their boy.
Winding through life, runs a river of tears
flowing deep with emotions with each passing year.
Tears of pain and joy, tears of gain and loss
Time and again we must cross the river of tears.
Sooner or later we'll cross
The river of tears

name: Colorado Kool-Aid
author: Johnny Paycheck
lyrics:
Well, I was sittin' in this beer joint down in Houston, Texas
Was drinkin' Colorado Cool-Aid and talkin' to some Mexicans
An' we was, what's that you say?
What's Colorado Cool-Aid?
Well, it's a can of Coors brewed from a mountain stream
It'll set your head on fire an' make your kidneys scream
Oh, it sure is fine
Yeah, we was havin' ourselves one of them real good times
But you know just as sure as any beer joint you've ever been in
There's some big, mean drunk who just ain't got no friends
Yeah, he wants to fight
He's gonna whip everything in sight
Well, he took him a big cold swallow of beer
And he walked over and spit in my Mexican friends ear
Sure enough - that made my buddy real mad
That's somethin' like he ain't never had
Well, Sir, he pulled out a big, long switch blade knife
Quick as a whistle he began to slice
That big mean drunk stood back, his face full of tears
Lookin' down at the floor, at one of his ears
Ha, he cut that thing off even with the sideburns
Well, ya might say the little Mexican fella, he just didn't give a dern
But he was a gentleman about it - An' bent over and with a half way grin
Picked it up and handed it back to him
He said, "Now big man, the next time you get the urge to spit a little beer
You just open up your hand there and spit it in your own ear
Won't be no trouble that way", that's what I heard him say
And I said, "Barmaid,
set us up
a round of that Colorado Cool-Aid
And while you're up there, bring this big fella here, a box of Bandaids"
Now let me tell you
if you're ever ridin' down in south of Texas
And you decide to stop an' drink some Colorado Cool-Aid
An' maybe talk to some Mexicans
An' you get the urge to get a little tough
Better make damn sure you got your knife proof ear-muffs
Hey, ain't that right, big man?
I SAID, AIN'T THAT RIGHT, BIG MAN?
Ah, hell - he can't hear,
not on this side anyway, he ain't got no ear!
Hey barmaid, bring us all a big, tall glass of that Colorado Cool-Aid
How about it?
How you doin' there, big man? Still got your ear there in your hand?
